{{Refimprove|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox song | name = Counterfeit God | cover = | alt = | type = single | artist = [[Black Label Society]] | album = [[Stronger Than Death]] | released = 2000 | format = | recorded = | studio = | venue = | genre = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]] | length = 4:18 | label = [[Spitfire Records|Spitfire]] | writer = [[Zakk Wylde]] | producer = Zakk Wylde | prev_title = Born to Lose | prev_year = 1999 | next_title = Bleed for Me | next_year = 2002 | misc = {{Extra track listing | album = [[Hellbilly Deluxe]] | type = single | prev_track = Superterrorizer | track = Counterfeit God | track_no = 6 | next_track = Ain't Life Grand }} }} "'''Counterfeit God'''" is a [[single (music)|single]] by [[Black Label Society]], featured on their 2000 [[studio album]] ''[[Stronger Than Death]]''.
==Background== The song is about [[televangelist]]s, much like the earlier [[Ozzy Osbourne]] song which Zakk co-wrote, "[[Miracle Man (Ozzy Osbourne song)|Miracle Man]]", which dealt with the hypocrisy of [[Jimmy Swaggart]]. In a 2000 interview, Wylde (who is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]) said, "I saw a TV evangelist. This guy sells out arenas, and he touches people on the head, and they're supposed to be blind, and then they're not blind anymore. That's the biggest backstabbing version of God I've ever...[[Anton LaVey]]'s got nothing over this guy. That's pure [[Satanism]] to me. He's backstabbing God so bad it's not even funny. People are paying money for that, and believe in that. How the hell are they believing it? This guy's playing God. To me, it's pure [[blasphemy]]."
==Music video== The [[music video]] features actor [[Mark Wahlberg]] as a stand-in for the band's bassist, because they did not have one at the time.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1431836/wahlbergs-dragon-megadeth-more-to-play-la/ Wahlberg's "Dragon," Megadeth, More To Play L.A.]</ref> It also includes Rick Phillips, a teacher at [[Valencia High School (Santa Clarita, California)|Valencia High School]]. [[Steve Gibb]] appears as the character painted as a skeleton and carrying chains; not long after this Gibb joined as bassist.
==Popular culture== "Counterfeit God" is the entrance theme of [[Martin Stone (wrestler)|Martin Stone]], a British [[professional wrestling|wrestler]] currently under the RQW [[professional wrestling promotion|promotion]].
