{{Infobox saint |name=Teresa Helena Higginson |birth_date={{birthdate|1844|5|27}} |birth_place=[[Holywell, Flintshire]], [[Wales]] |death_date={{dda|1905|3|15|1844|5|27}} |death_place=[[Chudleigh]], [[Devon]], [[England]] |feast_day= |venerated_in=[[Catholic Church]] |image=Teresa Helena Higginson Servant of God.jpg |imagesize= |caption=[[Photograph]] of Teresa Helena Higginson |titles=Servant of God |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= }}
'''Teresa Helena Higginson''' (27 May 1844 – 15 March 1905) was an [[English people|English]] Roman Catholic mystic.
==Life== Higginson was born in [[Holywell, Flintshire|Holywell]], [[Flintshire]], Wales in 1844 where her parents were staying whilst of pilgrimage to the shrine of St. Winefride.<ref name=am>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Teresa-Helena-Higginson-Servant-Crucified/dp/0852441819 Teresa Helena Higginson], Amazon, Retrieved 24 November 2015</ref> Her father Robert Francis Higginson was a Catholic and his wife was a convert. Higginson went to a convent school in Nottingham, and became a schoolteacher at [[Bootle]].<ref>Mary Heimann, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0ZRDrZcM3zUC&lpg=PA43&ots=1c1M4Qpd6n&dq=Teresa%20Higginson&pg=SL20-PA50#v=onepage ''Catholic Devotion in Victorian England''] (Clarendon Press 1995): 150. {{ISBN|9780198205975}}</ref>
During her life Higginson's hands and feet bled in a way known as [[stigmata]],<ref name=am/> she went into prayer trances that lasted days, and she "violently re-enacted" the scenes in the [[Stations of the Cross]].<ref>Mary Heimann, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0ZRDrZcM3zUC&lpg=PA43&ots=1c1M4Qpd6n&dq=Teresa%20Higginson&pg=PA43#v=onepage ''Catholic Devotion in Victorian England''] (Clarendon Press 1995): 43. {{ISBN|9780198205975}}</ref>
Higginson died in [[Chudleigh]] and was declared a [[Servant of God]].<ref>[http://www.teresahigginson.com/ Life story], TeresaHigginson.com, Retrieved 24 November 2015</ref>
==Legacy== Higginson was discussed as a possible candidate for [[canonization]] in 1928.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5056107/teresa_helena_higginson_sainthood/ "Woman of Prayer-Trance Likely to be Made Saint"] ''Wilkes-Barre Times Leader'' (21 November 1928): 10. via [[Newspapers.com]]{{open access}}</ref> Many letters written by Higginson are in the archives at [[St Augustine's Abbey, Ramsgate]], with duplicates at the [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral|Metropolitan Cathedral of Christ the King Liverpool]].<ref>[http://bollandlowe.net/dev/met-cath/history-heritage/cathedral-diocesan-archives/ Metropolitan Cathedral of Christ the King Liverpool, Archives.]</ref>
